def: Browse; also, a place abounding with shrubs where animals maybrowse.Browsings for the deer. Howell.
A companion in amusements or sports; a playmate. Shak.
An uncouth or disagreable sound of words, owing to theconcurrence of harsh letters or syllables. "Cacophonies of allkinds." Pope.
To loose from pins; to remove the pins from; to unfasten; as,to unpin a frock; to unpin a frame.
The state or symptoms characteristic of asystole.
The immersion of the body in water; as to take one's usualbathe. Edin. Rev.
Used in sexual union; as, the copulatory organs of insects.
Power; strength; might; force; potency. " Youths of puissance."Tennyson.The power and puissance of the king. Shak.
Capable of being sublimed or sublimated.-- Sub*lim"a*ble*ness, n. Boyle.
